Hãy học và ghi nhớ đoạn sau giúp tôi
How to learn anything 10x faster with the Feynman Technique

Be honest. You've ever said, "Yeah, I studied it." But if someone took your notes away and said, "Explain it." Your brain would go, "Windows shutting down." That's not because you're dumb. That's because your brain learned to recognize, not understand. And today, we fix that permanently. The real problem, most people miss this.
Most people think learning is about input, reading, watching, highlighting, rewriting notes. But the brain doesn't learn by consuming. It learns by reconstructing. The Fineman technique forces reconstruction. That's why it feels uncomfortable. And that's why it works. Level one, the explain like I'm 10 rule but smarter.
Everyone knows the step. Almost no one does it correctly. Wrong way. Photosynthesis is when plants convert light energy into chemical energy using chlorophyll. That's just memorization cosplay. Right way. Plants eat sunlight the way we eat food. Sunlight goes in, energy comes out, plant survives. If your explanation sounds like a textbook, you failed.
Your goal is metaphors, everyday language, stupidly simple logic. because your brain stores meaning, not sentences. Level two, gap hunting. This is where 10 times speed happens. Here's the secret most students never realize. Studying what you don't know beats reviewing what you do know. When you explain and get stuck, do not. Reread the whole chapter.
Restart from page one. Panic. Instead ask, "What exact sentence can I not explain?" That sentence is the bottleneck. Fix one bottleneck, the whole system improves. This is why top learners feel fast. They're not learning more. They're wasting less time. Level three, compression. Turn five pages into five lines.
Advanced learners don't add knowledge, they compress it. After learning a topic, challenge yourself. Can I explain this in five sentences? Then can I explain it in three? Then can I explain it in one sentence? This forces your brain to identify what matters, what's noise, what's core logic. If you can compress it, you control it.
Level four, out loud explanation. The lie detector. Silent studying is dangerous because your brain can fake clarity silently. Speaking out loud activates auditory processing. Error detection. Working memory. Translation. No lies allowed. If you stumble, hesitate, or pause awkwardly. Good.
That hesitation is literally your brain saying, "We need to fix this part." Say it again. Cleaner, simpler, sharper. Level five, the why, how, what, flip. Advanced. Most people learn in this order. What? How? Why? Elite learners flip it. Why? How? What? Example. What is inflation? Why does inflation happen? How does it affect money? What is it called? The brain remembers causes better than definitions. Always start with why.
The science short but powerful. The Fineman technique works because it uses active recall pulling info from memory, elaboration, connecting ideas, error-based learning, fixing mistakes, and coding depth meaning overmemorization. This combo builds durable memory, not exam only knowledge. The 15-minute Fineman routine.
Use this daily. One, pick one concept. Two, explain it on paper or aloud. No notes. Three, mark where you get stuck. Four, fix only that gap. Five, reexlain. Simpler. Six, compress to three sentences. Done. No burnout, no fake productivity, maximum return. Common mistakes. Don't do this. Trying to findment an entire chapter using fancy words to feel smart.
Writing instead of explaining avoiding confusion. Confusion is not the enemy. Avoiding confusion is most people don't fail because they're lazy. They fail because they mistake recognition for understanding. The Fineman technique removes that illusion. So next time you study, don't ask, "Did I read it?" Ask, "Can I teach it without notes?" If yes, you own it.
If no, you found your next upgrade. Now go turn your brain into a weapon. Try this technique today and tell me in the comments what you learned using it. And don't forget to like, subscribe, and share with a friend who says, "I studied but can't explain anything.